    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/pX6ku.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 1275953,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1231230,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1231230/ankur-singhal",
                "reputation": 26120,
                "display_name": "Ankur Singhal",
                "accept_rate": 76
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1410506032,
            "creation_date": 1410504555,
            "body": "<p><code>String<\/code> objects created with the new operator do not refer to objects in the string pool but can be made to using String\u2019s <code>intern()<\/code> method. The <code>java.lang.String.intern()<\/code> returns an interned <code>String<\/code>, that is, one that has an entry in the global <code>String literal pool<\/code>. If the <code>String<\/code> is not already in the global <code>String literal pool<\/code>, then it will be added.<\/p>\n\n<p>Each time your code create a string literal, the JVM checks the string literal pool first. If the string already exists in the pool, a reference to the pooled instance returns. If the string does not exist in the pool, a new String object instantiates, then is placed in the pool.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>String[] stringArray = new String[] { \"abc\", \"xyz\" };\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Executing this line there are two String literals created \"<code>abc<\/code>\" and \"<code>xyz<\/code>\" in <code>PERMGEN space<\/code>.<\/p>\n\n<p>All objects, except <code>string literals<\/code>, are created on the heap. From <code>Java 7<\/code>, string literals are created on the <code>heap<\/code> as well.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 25802386,
            "question_id": 25802249,
            "last_edit_date": 1410506032
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/lUM5Z.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 52616,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 157247,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/157247/t-j-crowder",
                "reputation": 1081806,
                "display_name": "T.J. Crowder",
                "accept_rate": 91
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1410505311,
            "creation_date": 1410504561,
            "body": "<blockquote>\n  <p>Obviously it will create one object in heap, my doubt is it will create <code>\"apple\"<\/code> in SCP(String Constant Pool) also. (Lets assume \"apple\" is not there in SCP).<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Yes. When the class containing that code is loaded, <code>\"apple\"<\/code> will be added to the SCP if it's not already there. Then, later, when that line of code <em>executes<\/em>, a <code>String<\/code> object is created on the heap. The heap object will be different from the SCP object, but they'll both use the <em>same<\/em> underlying character array, as we can see from the Java 8 source:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public String(String original) {\n    this.value = original.value;\n    this.hash = original.hash;\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>or the Java 7 source:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public String(String original) {\n    int size = original.count;\n    char[] originalValue = original.value;\n    char[] v;\n    if (originalValue.length &gt; size) {\n        // The array representing the String is bigger than the new\n        // String itself.  Perhaps this constructor is being called\n        // in order to trim the baggage, so make a copy of the array.\n        int off = original.offset;\n        v = Arrays.copyOfRange(originalValue, off, off+size);\n    } else {\n        // The array representing the String is the same\n        // size as the String, so no point in making a copy.\n        v = originalValue;\n    }\n    this.offset = 0;\n    this.count = size;\n    this.value = v;\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Since <code>\"apple\"<\/code> is in the SCP and its value length is the same as its size, the <code>else<\/code> is used and both end up using the same character array.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 25802390,
            "question_id": 25802249,
            "last_edit_date": 1410505311
        }
    ],
